I agree with this: even more important than an open development model is
an open testing model (IMO).

The fvwm-workers list is the right place to announce alpha tests.  Once
one is announced, everyone on the list who has the time and motivation
should grab and test it, and report success/failure to the author (or
even to the entire workers list).  It will be up to Brady to decide when
a release has had "enough" testing... if he doesn't feel that it has he
should goose the fvwm-workers list and get more people to check it, and
probably give an idea of what parts are light.  It's purely up to him to
decide what's "enough" testing, obviously.

Perhaps the current readership of the lists is too dispersed and needs
to be retargeted, but a simple email announcement to each list restating
its purpose and how to get on/off the one(s) you don't want to be on
should be sufficient.  Also, the "hello" messages for these lists should
be reviewed and it should be made clear that if you're not willing to
run an alpha WM, you shouldn't be on the workers list.

One thing the Perl folks have done recently is include a script as part
of their test suite that can automatically mail a "success/failure"
report, grabbing such useful info as the system type, etc.  That might
be handy.

  roae> Thank you "Brady Montz", for taking the gauntlet.
  roae> And thank you "Chuck" for picking up the gauntlet

Ditto, in spades.

Hey, does anyone know what ever happened to Rob?  Is he still around on
these lists or anywhere else?

Long time no hear.

