OK, finally. 2.0.47 is almost ready. I've been using it for a few days and it
seems to work for me :-)

I've decided that I'll just release it to fvwm-workers for final testing
before announcing it to the fvwm list. 

I'd like to have a public CVS repository set up ASAP. If possible, I'd like it
set up when I release 2.0.47 (I won't hold up fvwm 2.0.47 unless I have a
solid date on when CVS will be setup). I've only used CVS in a local setting,
so it's probably best if somebody with more experience sets that up (Jason
Tibbitts volunteered I recall).

Here's my proposal:

After 2.0.47, fvwm 2.0 goes into a feature freeze. So, I'd like two source
directories, one for 2.0.*, and one for fvwm 2.3 (when 2.0.* has stabilised
I'd like to release it as 2.2 so we're matching the linux and xemacs
convention of odd minor numbers denoting stable releases. So, 2.1 will have
to be skipped). 

I'd like to able to control read/write access to each source tree. Bonus
points for a page on the website which is automatically updated to list who
has access. 

I think a good initial policy might be that only I have write access to the
"stable" code, and everybody on the fvwm-workers list having full access to
the "unstable" code. I see no reason why everything shouldn't be
world-readable. 

It would be nice if all checkins resulted in mail being sent to fvwm-workers. 

Suggestions? Comments?

