        OK, I tinkered with menus.c a little, and the following patch
seems to restore the sticky menu handling that we've been used to in
fvwm2.

        Since I've not had the time to dig too deeply into the menu
code, though, my concerns are: what was the actual intent of the new
code, does this patch produce any nasty side effects (haven't seen 'em
yet), and are there possibly pieces missing from the version we have
in 2.0.47b? (Hmm.... I just noticed that WinList exhibits the same
no-stick-on-click behavior - this patch doesn't affect it.)

        Also, Greg, I'm completely at a loss to understand why it
seemed to work differently for you. In any case, does this look like
a reasonable change?


diff -u -r fvwm-2.0.47b/fvwm/menus.c fvwm-2.0.47b-patched/fvwm/menus.c
--- fvwm-2.0.47b/fvwm/menus.c   Tue Jun 23 15:58:30 1998
+++ fvwm-2.0.47b-patched/fvwm/menus.c   Thu Jun 25 00:16:15 1998
@@ -533,7 +533,7 @@
          mi = FindEntry(&x_offset);
          /* hold the menu up when the button is released 
             for the first time if released OFF of the menu */
-         if(fSticks && !mi) {
+         if(fSticks) {
            fSticks = FALSE;
             continue;
            /* break; */



 
